{"title_page": "Yohannan V", "text_new": "'''ashutosh chopra ''' is [[a event organiser ]].\n\n==Life==\nYohannan was [[bishop of Shenna|bishop of al-Sin or Shenna]] when he was consecrated as [[archbishop of Fars]] by [[Mari (Nestorian Patriarch)|Patriarch{{nbsp}}Mari]] (r.{{nbsp}}987\u2013999).{{sfnp|Sliba ibn Yuhanna|14th c.|p=94}} He ordained [[Elijah of Nisibis|Elijah]], the future archbishop of Nisibis, at the monastery of Mar Shem\u02bfon in his role as bishop of Shenna on 15 September 994.<ref>[[Elijah of Nisibis]], ''Chronography'', i. 112.</ref>\n\nAccording to Bar Hebraeus:\n\n<blockquote>\nAfter the catholicus [[Mari (Nestorian Patriarch)|Mari]] had fulfilled his office for fourteen years, he died in the first month of the year 390 of the Arabs, that is to say on the twenty-eighth day of the former ''kanun'' [December] in the year 1311 of the Greeks [AD 999].  He was succeeded by Yunanis II,{{efn|Bar Hebraeus called Yohannan V and his predecessor [[Yohannan IV]] (900\u201305) Yunanis, an alternative name for Yohannan more frequently used in the Syrian Orthodox Church than in the Church of the East.  For Bar Hebraeus, therefore, he is the patriarch 'Yunanis II'.  The Nestorian sources correctly style him Yohannan V.}} the metropolitan of Fars.  This man, when he heard of the death of Mari, went to Shiraz, to the governor Baha al-Dawla, and won his support.  Baha al-Dawla thereupon ordered that he should become catholicus.  When the nobles of Baghdad heard that he had assumed the leadership uncanonically, by going to the governor's palace without being either elected or acclaimed, they were deeply offended, but were unable to oppose the edict.  And so he was consecrated catholicus against the wishes of his people.<ref>Bar Hebraeus, ''Ecclesiastical Chronicle'' (ed. Abeloos and Lamy), ii. 260\u20132</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nYohannan consecrated [[Elijah of Nisibis|Elijah]] as [[bishop of Beth Nuhadra]] (present-day [[Dohuk]], [[Iraq]]) on 15{{nbsp}}February 1002.{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 112}}\n\nBar Hebraeus also reported in his Ecclesiastical Chronicle that [[Abdisho]], the Metropolitan of Merv, wrote and informed Catholicos Yohannan between 1007 and 1009 concerning the restoration of 200,000 Karaits to the Church of the East requesting directions concerning the observance of Lent for the Karaits lived almost exclusively on Milk and Meat and could not give up both. It is reported that Yohannan responded that a fast which we now call [[Molokan]] should be permitted to them.<ref>I. Gilman & H. Klimkeit, Christians in Asia before 1500, Curzon, 1999. pp 226-229</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\nBrief accounts of Yohannan's patriarchate are given in the ''Ecclesiastical Chronicle'' of the Jacobite writer Bar Hebraeus (''floruit'' 1280) and in the ecclesiastical histories of the Nestorian writers Mari (twelfth-century), {{transl|ar|DIN|\u02bf}}Amr (fourteenth-century) and [[Sliba ibn Yuhanna|Sliba]] (fourteenth-century)\n\n* Abbeloos, J. B., and Lamy, T. J., ''Bar Hebraeus, Chronicon Ecclesiasticum'' (3 vols, Paris, 1877)\n* Assemani, J. A., ''De Catholicis seu Patriarchis Chaldaeorum et Nestorianorum'' (Rome, 1775)\n* Brooks, E. W., ''Eliae Metropolitae Nisibeni Opus Chronologicum'' (Rome, 1910)\n* Gismondi, H., ''Maris, Amri, et Salibae: De Patriarchis Nestorianorum Commentaria I: Amri et Salibae Textus'' (Rome, 1896)\n* Gismondi, H., ''Maris, Amri, et Salibae: De Patriarchis Nestorianorum Commentaria II: Maris textus arabicus et versio Latina'' (Rome, 1899)\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Mari (Nestorian Patriarch)|Mari]] <br> (987\u2013999)}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East|Catholicus-Patriarch of the East]]|years=(1000\u20131011)}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Yohannan VI]] <br> (1012\u20131016)}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Patriarchs of the Church of the East}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yohannan 05}}\n[[Category:Patriarchs of the Church of the East]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Assyrian Church of the East]]\n[[Category:Nestorians in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n", "text_old": "'''Yohannan V''' was [[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East|Patriarch of the Church of the East]] from 1000 to 1011.\n\n==Life==\nYohannan was [[bishop of Shenna|bishop of al-Sin or Shenna]] when he was consecrated as [[archbishop of Fars]] by [[Mari (Nestorian Patriarch)|Patriarch{{nbsp}}Mari]] (r.{{nbsp}}987\u2013999).{{sfnp|Sliba ibn Yuhanna|14th c.|p=94}} He ordained [[Elijah of Nisibis|Elijah]], the future archbishop of Nisibis, at the monastery of Mar Shem\u02bfon in his role as bishop of Shenna on 15 September 994.<ref>[[Elijah of Nisibis]], ''Chronography'', i. 112.</ref>\n\nAccording to Bar Hebraeus:\n\n<blockquote>\nAfter the catholicus [[Mari (Nestorian Patriarch)|Mari]] had fulfilled his office for fourteen years, he died in the first month of the year 390 of the Arabs, that is to say on the twenty-eighth day of the former ''kanun'' [December] in the year 1311 of the Greeks [AD 999].  He was succeeded by Yunanis II,{{efn|Bar Hebraeus called Yohannan V and his predecessor [[Yohannan IV]] (900\u201305) Yunanis, an alternative name for Yohannan more frequently used in the Syrian Orthodox Church than in the Church of the East.  For Bar Hebraeus, therefore, he is the patriarch 'Yunanis II'.  The Nestorian sources correctly style him Yohannan V.}} the metropolitan of Fars.  This man, when he heard of the death of Mari, went to Shiraz, to the governor Baha al-Dawla, and won his support.  Baha al-Dawla thereupon ordered that he should become catholicus.  When the nobles of Baghdad heard that he had assumed the leadership uncanonically, by going to the governor's palace without being either elected or acclaimed, they were deeply offended, but were unable to oppose the edict.  And so he was consecrated catholicus against the wishes of his people.<ref>Bar Hebraeus, ''Ecclesiastical Chronicle'' (ed. Abeloos and Lamy), ii. 260\u20132</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nYohannan consecrated [[Elijah of Nisibis|Elijah]] as [[bishop of Beth Nuhadra]] (present-day [[Dohuk]], [[Iraq]]) on 15{{nbsp}}February 1002.{{sfn|''Chronography''|loc=i. 112}}\n\nBar Hebraeus also reported in his Ecclesiastical Chronicle that [[Abdisho]], the Metropolitan of Merv, wrote and informed Catholicos Yohannan between 1007 and 1009 concerning the restoration of 200,000 Karaits to the Church of the East requesting directions concerning the observance of Lent for the Karaits lived almost exclusively on Milk and Meat and could not give up both. It is reported that Yohannan responded that a fast which we now call [[Molokan]] should be permitted to them.<ref>I. Gilman & H. Klimkeit, Christians in Asia before 1500, Curzon, 1999. pp 226-229</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\nBrief accounts of Yohannan's patriarchate are given in the ''Ecclesiastical Chronicle'' of the Jacobite writer Bar Hebraeus (''floruit'' 1280) and in the ecclesiastical histories of the Nestorian writers Mari (twelfth-century), {{transl|ar|DIN|\u02bf}}Amr (fourteenth-century) and [[Sliba ibn Yuhanna|Sliba]] (fourteenth-century)\n\n* Abbeloos, J. B., and Lamy, T. J., ''Bar Hebraeus, Chronicon Ecclesiasticum'' (3 vols, Paris, 1877)\n* Assemani, J. A., ''De Catholicis seu Patriarchis Chaldaeorum et Nestorianorum'' (Rome, 1775)\n* Brooks, E. W., ''Eliae Metropolitae Nisibeni Opus Chronologicum'' (Rome, 1910)\n* Gismondi, H., ''Maris, Amri, et Salibae: De Patriarchis Nestorianorum Commentaria I: Amri et Salibae Textus'' (Rome, 1896)\n* Gismondi, H., ''Maris, Amri, et Salibae: De Patriarchis Nestorianorum Commentaria II: Maris textus arabicus et versio Latina'' (Rome, 1899)\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{S-start}}\