gn:center;\" | LLB || [[Jack Pardee]]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Nick Buoniconti]]\u2021 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | MLB || [[Myron Pottios]]\n|-\n| [[Mike Kolen]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | RLB || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Chris Hanburger]]\u2021\n|-\n| [[Lloyd Mumphord]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | LCB || [[Pat Fischer]]\n|-\n| [[Curtis Johnson (cornerback)|Curtis Johnson]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | RCB || [[Mike Bass]]\n|-\n| [[Dick Anderson]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | LS || [[Brig Owens]]\n|-\n| [[Jake Scott]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | RS || [[Roosevelt Taylor]]\n|}\n\n==Officials==\n*'''Referee:''' [[Tommy Bell (American football official)|Tom Bell]] #7 second Super Bowl (III)\n*'''Umpire:''' [[Lou Palazzi]] #51 second Super Bowl (IV)\n*'''Head Linesman:''' Tony Veteri Sr. #36 second Super Bowl (II)\n*'''Line Judge:''' [[Bruce Alford Sr.|Bruce Alford]] #24 second Super Bowl (II)\n*'''Back Judge:''' [[Tom Kelleher (American football official)|Tom Kelleher]] #25 second Super Bowl (IV)\n*'''Field Judge:''' Tony Skover #50 first Super Bowl\n*'''Alternate Referee:''' [[Fred Silva]] #81, first Super Bowl, later worked Super Bowl XIV on field \n*'''Alternate Umpire:''' Walt Parker #41 second Super Bowl (III), first as an alternate<ref>{{cite web | url=https://meangreensports.com/news/2010/1/25/North_Texas_Hall_of_Famer_Walt_Parker_Dies.aspx | title=North Texas Hall of Famer Walt Parker Dies | publisher=University of North Texas | accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Note: A seven-official system was not used until 1978. Back Judge and Field Judge swapped titles prior to the [[1998 NFL season|1998]].''\n\n==Super Bowl postgame news==\nAs Shula was being carried off the field after the end of the game, a kid who shook his hand stripped off his watch. Shula got down, chased after the kid, and retrieved his watch.<ref name=\"Dave Hyde p.268\">Dave Hyde, ''Still Perfect!'' p. 268.</ref>\n\n[[Manny Fernandez (American football)|Manny Fernandez]] was a strong contender for MVP. Wrote Nick Buoniconti, \"It was the game of his life\u2013in fact, it was the most dominant game by a defensive lineman in the history of the game, and he would never be given much credit for it. They should have given out two game balls and made Manny Fernandez the co-MVP with Jake Scott.\"<ref name=Buoniconti/> Larry Csonka also said he thought Fernandez should have been the MVP.<ref>Larry Csonka and Jim Kiick, with Dave Anderson, ''Always on the Run'', p. 220.</ref> The MVP was selected by [[Dick Schaap]], the editor of ''[[Sport (US magazine)|SPORT]]'' magazine. Schaap admitted later that he had been out late the previous night, struggled to watch the defense-dominated game, and was not aware that Fernandez had 17 tackles.<ref>Dave Hyde, ''Still Perfect!'', pp. 260\u2013261.</ref>\n\nWhen Garo Yepremian went back to the Dolphins' sideline after his botched field goal attempt, Nick Buoniconti told him that if they lost he would \"Hang you up by one of your ties.\"<ref name=\"Dave Hyde p264\"/> Yepremian would joke to reporters after the game, \"This is the first time the goat of the game is in the winner's locker room.\"<ref name=\"B\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=tfSmAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA157&lpg=PA157&dq=Yepremian+coin+toss#v=onepage&q=Yepremian%20coin%20toss&f=false | title=Placekicking in the NFL: A History and Analysis | publisher=McFarland | author=Gonsalves, Rick | year=2013 | pages=157\u2013160| isbn=9781476600512 }}</ref> But Yepremian would be so traumatized by his botched attempt that he had to be helped from the post-game party by his brother because of a stress-induced stabbing pain down his right side. Depressed, he spent two weeks in seclusion until he was cheered up by a letter, apparently from Shula, praising him for his contributions to the team and urging him to ignore criticism. Yepremian kept the letter and mentioned it to Shula in 2000, but Shula had no knowledge of it. They concluded the letter was actually written by Shula's wife Dorothy, who died from [[breast cancer]] in 1991. She had signed her husband's name to it.<ref>Dave Hyde, ''Still Perfect!'' p.283.</ref> Nevertheless, \"Garo's Gaffe\" made Yepremian famous and led to a lucrative windfall of speaking engagements and endorsements. \"It's been a blessing\", said Yepremian, who passed away in 2015.<ref name=\"Dave Hyde p.268\"/>\n\nThe same teams met 10 years later in [[Super Bowl XVII]], which was also played in the Los Angeles area, at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]]. The Redskins won that game, 27\u201317. Two starters from Miami's undefeated team, guard Bob Kuechenberg and defensive end Vern Den Herder, were still active during the strike-shortened [[1982 NFL season|1982 season]]. The Redskins had no players remaining from Super Bowl VII on their Super Bowl XVII roster. The last member of the 1972 Redskins still active with the franchise, offensive tackle Terry Hermeling, retired after the 1980 season.\n\nRedskins linebacker and defensive captain Jack Pardee retired immediately following this game, ending a 16-year career. He coached the [[Chicago Bears]] for three seasons (1975\u201377) before succeeding Allen as Redskins coach in 1978. Pardee was fired following a 6\u201310 campaign in 1980 and was replaced by [[Joe Gibbs]], who led the Redskins to three Super Bowl championships ([[Super Bowl XVII|XVII]], [[Super Bowl XXII|XXII]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]]) and 171 victories to earn induction into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]. After coaching the [[Houston Gamblers]] of the [[United States Football League]] in 1984 and '85, Pardee coached at the [[Houston Cougars football|University of Houston]] (1987\u201389) and the [[Houston Oilers]] (1990\u201394). \n\nThe Miami Dolphins became the second team to win the Super Bowl after losing it the previous year. They are the last team to do so until the [[New England Patriots]] in [[Super Bowl LIII]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References/Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [http://www.superbowl.com/ Super Bowl official website]\n*{{cite book | title=2006 NFL Record and Fact Book | publisher=Time Inc. Home Entertainment | isbn=1-933405-32-5 | url=https://archive.org/details/2006nflrecordfac00edit }}\n*{{cite book | title=Total Football II: The Official Encyclopedia of the National Football League | publisher=[[Harper Collins]] | isbn=1-933405-32-5 | url=https://archive.org/details/2006nflrecordfac00edit }}\n*{{cite book | title=The Official NFL Encyclopedia Pro Football | publisher=NAL Books | isbn=0-453-00431-8}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Sporting News Complete Super Bowl Book 1995 | isbn=0-89204-523-X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{YouTube|id=CkLiT1jV5Ms|title=Super Bowl VII: NFL Full Game}}\n* https://www.pro-football-reference.com \u2013 Large online database of NFL data and statistics\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/super/superbowl-plays.htm Super Bowl play-by-plays] from ''[[USA Today]]'' (Last accessed September 28, 2005)\n* [http://www.predictem.com/nfl/previous.php Past Super Bowl Matchups \u2013 Winners \u2013 Odds From Predict 'Em.com, Last Accessed May 4, 2012.]\n\n{{Super Bowl}}\n{{Super Bowl VII}}\n{{Miami Dolphins}}\n{{Washington Redskins}}\n{{1972 NFL season by team}}\n{{NFLC-SuperBowl}}\n{{NFL on NBC}}\n\n[[Category:Super Bowl|Super Bowl 007]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins postseason]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins postseason]]\n[[Category:National Football League in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1972 National Football League season]]\n[[Category:1973 in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:January 1973 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1973 in sports in California]]\n", "name_user": "Wkyken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOfficials", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_VII"}
{"title_page": "Cizre Dam", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 = Cizre Dam\n| image                = \n| image_caption        = \n| name_official        = Cizre Baraji\n| dam_crosses          = [[Tigris River]]\n| location             = [[Cizre]], [[\u015e\u0131rnak Province]], [[Turkey]]\n| dam_type             = Embankment, earth-fill\n| dam_length           ={{Convert|740|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_height           ={{Convert|46|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_elevation_crest  = {{Convert|409|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| plant_hydraulic_head ={{Convert|36|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (gross)\n| dam_width_crest      ={{Convert|15|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_width_base       ={{Convert|190|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_volume           ={{Convert|3300000|m3|acre.ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| spillway_type        =Service overflow, controlled-chute\n| spillway_capacity    ={{Convert|18700|m3/s|ft3/s|0|abbr=on}}\n| purpose              = Power, irrigation\n| status               = P\n| construction_began   = \n| opening              = \n| cost                 = \n| owner                = [[State Hydraulic Works]]\n| res_name             = Cizre Reservoir\n| res_capacity_total   = {{Convert|360000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| res_capacity_active  = {{Convert|208000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| res_capacity_inactive= {{Convert|152000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| res_elevation        = {{Convert|404.4|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| res_max_length       = {{Convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| res_surface          = {{Convert|21|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}<ref name=EIADSI>{{cite web|title=Ilisu Dam Environmental Impact Assessment|url=http://www2.dsi.gov.tr/ilisu/ilisu_ced_eng.pdf|publisher=State Hydraulic Works|accessdate=20 May 2013|pages=TABLE 2\u20133 (PDF pgs. 112\u2013113)|year=2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926095504/http://www2.dsi.gov.tr/ilisu/ilisu_ced_eng.pdf|archivedate=26 September 2015}}</ref>\n| res_catchment        ={{Convert|38295|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}\n| res_max_depth        =\n| plant_operator       =\n| plant_commission     = \n| plant_turbines       = 3 x 80 MW [[Francis-type]]\n| plant_capacity       = 240 [[Megawatt|MW]]\n| plant_annual_gen     = \n| plant_decommission   =\n| location_map         =Turkey\n| location_map_caption =\n| coordinates          = {{coord|37|21|47|N|42|09|17|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| website              = http://ilisuprojesi.com/index.php?lang=en{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n| extra                =\n}}\nThe '''Cizre Dam''' is a proposed [[dam]] on the [[Tigris River]] north of [[Cizre|Cizre, Turkey]].  The Cizre Dam is to be built in conjunction and downstream of the [[Ilisu Dam]].  The Cizre Dam is also one of the planned dams of Turkey's [[Southeastern Anatolia Project]] (GAP).  The purpose of the Cizre Dam is irrigation, hydro-power and to control the tailwaters of the Ilisu Dam.\n\nA tender for the Cizre Dam was unsuccessfully issued in May 2008 but another issue on 15 May 2014 left [[Zorlu Energy]] as the winning bidder.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.diclehaber.com/tr/news/content/view/401050?from=3392673384 | title=Cizre dam will destroy thousands of years of history turns out to tender | publisher=D\u0130HA - Dicle News Agency | date=12 May 2014 | accessdate=12 May 2014 | language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.borsagundem.com/haber/zorlu-enerji-ihaleyi-kazanamadi/592872 | title=Zorlu Energy, Cizre Dam and HEPP projects that result in their favor for the tender announced | publisher=Borsa Gundem | date=15 May 2014 | accessdate=3 June 2014 | language=Turkish}}</ref> The Cizre Dam will have a hydro-power capacity of 240 MW and will provide irrigation for 121,000 hectares.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://memrieconomicblog.org/bin/content.cgi?news=865 | title=Turkey: Completion of Cizre Dam Tender Will Earn Treasury $3.2 Billion | publisher=Memri Economic | date=1 January 2008 | accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==